version: 1
display_name: VCFE-9X-000010 - The ESX host client must be configured with an idle session timeout.
global_description: |-
  The ESX host client is the UI served up by the host itself, outside of vCenter. ESX is not usually administered via this interface for long periods, and all users will be highly privileged. Implementing a mandatory session idle limit will ensure that orphaned, forgotten, or ignored sessions will be closed promptly.
osfinger: []  # API/proxy-managed control; not tied to a minion OS grain
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - VCFE-9X-000010
  srg:
    - SRG-OS-000029-VMM-000100
  cci:
    - CCI-000057
  nist:
    - AC-11 a
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_vsphere_esx:
    type: custom
    desc: The ESX host client must be configured with an idle session timeout.
    control_id: VCFE-9X-000010
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      From the vSphere Client, go to Hosts and Clusters.

      Select the ESX Host >> Configure >> System >> Advanced System Settings.

      Select the "UserVars.HostClientSessionTimeout" value and verify it is set to "900" or less.

      or

      From a PowerCLI command prompt while connected to the ESX host, run the following command:

      Get-VMHost | Get-AdvancedSetting -Name UserVars.HostClientSessionTimeout

      If the "UserVars.HostClientSessionTimeout" setting is not set to "900" or less, this is a finding.
    rationale: |-
      The ESX host client is the UI served up by the host itself, outside of vCenter. ESX is not usually administered via this interface for long periods, and all users will be highly privileged. Implementing a mandatory session idle limit will ensure that orphaned, forgotten, or ignored sessions will be closed promptly.
    remediation: |-
      From the vSphere Client, go to Hosts and Clusters.

      Select the ESX Host >> Configure >> System >> Advanced System Settings.

      Click "Edit". Select the "UserVars.HostClientSessionTimeout" value and configure it to "900".

      or

      From a PowerCLI command prompt while connected to the ESX host, run the following command:

      Get-VMHost | Get-AdvancedSetting -Name UserVars.HostClientSessionTimeout | Set-AdvancedSetting -Value "900"
